{{Infobox artifact | name = The Broomend of Crichie Stone | image = Broomend of Crichie Stone Circle (4) (geograph 5555392).jpg | image2 = | image_caption = | material = | size = | writing = | created = | discovered = | location = Port Elphinstone, [[Inverurie]], [[Aberdeenshire]] | coordinates = {{coord|57.2672 | -2.3677|type:edu|display=inline,title}} | classification = Class I incised stone | civilization = [[Picts|Picto-Scottish]] | symbols = {{Plainlist| * Pictish beast * Crescent and V-rod }} }}
The '''Broomend of Crichie Stone''' is a class I [[Pictish stones|Pictish stone]] that stands within a henge at Broomend of Crichie, Port Elphinstone, Inverurie, [[Aberdeenshire]], [[Scotland]]. It was placed within the henge in the 19th century. The stone bears the incised symbols of the Pictish beast and the crescent and V-rod.<ref name=Fraser>{{citation | title = The Pictish Symbol Stones of Scotland | publisher = Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historic Monuments of Scotland | last = Fraser | first = Iain | pages = 16 | location = Edinburgh | year = 2008}}</ref>
The henge, with the avenue, standing stones and the symbol stone, is a [[scheduled ancient monument]]. <ref> {{cite web|url=http://portal.historicenvironment.scot/designation/SM18|title=Broomend, henge, standing stones and symbol stoneSM18|publisher= Historic Environment Scotland|accessdate=8 September 2017}} </ref>
